This statue is haunting me. This statue, depicting refugees fleeing violence and persecution and migrants fighting for a better life, will not leave me the hell alone. 
I’m selfish. I want to enjoy my fall break and traveling with my friends, and keep my empathy and compassion on hold, as academic features to be examined. But this statue won’t let me. Because everywhere I go, there are people who don’t belong. People who are spilling out of buses and doorsteps, heading for a job that pays them too little. People who left their home behind them in fear or in hope. People whose eyes glance backward towards that home every day, while their hands work hard and long hours trying to build a new home in a new place. 
I see them, every day, on every corner,
accomplishing great feats of humanity - working, laughing, hoping, begging, being. 
I see them moving, because that is what humans do. They move in necessity and they leave home behind, and I do too. 
I guess what I’m saying is that I can’t get this statue out of my head because I see myself on that boat. & you know what? I see Jesus on that boat too, commanding the seas to be at peace, commanding us to be at peace. 
#angelsunawares #refugeeswelcome
